[227] assistant: No reportable security vulnerabilities survived the adversarial review.

One real reliability defect was reproduced: each Fly request reconstructs the issuer identity, defeating the shared verifier/JWKS cache. Two identical requests caused two JWKS fetches despite a five-minute cache header. It was rejected as a security finding because requests are rate-limited before authentication, fanout is one-for-one to a fixed Fly endpoint, and no authentication, authorization, secret, or token-minting bypass occurs.

Additional conclusions:

- Issuer and JWKS selection remain operator-controlled; arbitrary SSRF is prevented.
- RS256, issuer, temporal claims, scalar `aud`, and optional `azp` are enforced.
- Fly tokens cannot match GitHub Actions policy rules.
- No Fly allow rule currently exists, so Fly authentication cannot yet mint tokens.
- Before adding one, restore canonical consistency checks between `sub`, organization, app, and Machine claims. Fly documents `sub` as the Machine’s organization, app, and Machine identity. [Fly.io OIDC documentation](https://fly.io/docs/security/openid-connect/)

I recommend fixing the JWKS cache lifetime before publication despite its non-reportable severity.

